    <item>
      <title>Mass scaling</title>
      <link>https://vishvAsa.github.io/notes/general_biology/eukaryota/animal/bilatera/dutero-stome/chordata/vertebrata/osteichthyes/sarco-pterygia/tetrapoda/amniota/articles/MT/mass-scaling/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://vishvAsa.github.io/notes/general_biology/eukaryota/animal/bilatera/dutero-stome/chordata/vertebrata/osteichthyes/sarco-pterygia/tetrapoda/amniota/articles/MT/mass-scaling/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Source: &lt;a href=&#34;https://x.com/i/lists/934873690050740224&#34;&gt;TW&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The heaviest dinosaur, Argentinosaurus, is estimated to be at least 60-65 tons in mass.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;One of the lightest dinosaurs, the Ruby-throated hummingbird, is about 3 grams.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Hence, the same basic dinosaurian body plan allows for a mass scaling factor of about 20-21 million.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The blue whale is about 130 tons on average.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The lightest mammal, the Etruscan Shrew, is about 1.8 grams&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Hence, the same basic mammalian body plan allows for a mass scaling factor of about 72 million.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
